data.reasoningText:
Now I understand the codebase. The project has `<Nullable>enable</Nullable>` in the csproj, but each file has `#nullable disable` at the top to opt out.

I need to:
1. Remove `#nullable disable` from UserProfile.cs
2. Fix all resulting nullable warnings

Let me analyze UserProfile.cs with nullable enabled:

```csharp
public class UserProfile
{
    public string Name { get; set; }      // non-nullable, OK - set in constructor
    public string Bio { get; set; }       // This could be null (not set in constructor) → should be string?
    public string Email { get; set; }     // non-nullable, OK - set in constructor

    public UserProfile(string name, string email)
    {
        Name = name;
        Email = email;
    }

    public string GetDisplayName()
    {
        return Bio != null ? $"{Name} - {Bio}" : Name;
    }
}
```

The main issue is that `Bio` is declared as non-nullable but never initialized in the constructor, which will trigger a CS8618 warning about the property needing a non-null value when the constructor exits. I need to either make it nullable with `string?` or initialize it in the constructor.

Looking at the rest of the class, `Name` and `Email` are both properly set in the constructor so they're fine as non-nullable strings. The `GetDisplayName()` method is also safe since both return paths produce non-null values. Let me apply the fix and rebuild to confirm everything compiles cleanly.

